  '# Complete Guide to Chiang Mai Night Markets 2026

## Introduction

Chiang Mai''s night markets are legendary - a feast for the senses where you can shop for handicrafts, sample street food, get a massage, and soak in Thai culture all in one place. This comprehensive guide covers the best night markets, what to buy, how to bargain, and insider tips specifically for Israeli travelers.

## The Big Three: Must-Visit Markets

### 1. Sunday Walking Street (ถนนคนเดินวันอาทิตย์)

**Location**: Ratchadamnoen Road (Old City)
**Hours**: Every Sunday, 4 PM - 11 PM
**Best For**: Handicrafts, art, local products

**Why It''s Special**:
The Sunday Walking Street is the crown jewel of Chiang Mai''s night markets. The entire 1-kilometer stretch of Ratchadamnoen Road transforms into a pedestrian-only market with over 1,000 vendors.

**What to Buy**:
- Hand-painted umbrellas (200-500 THB)
- Silver jewelry (starting 300 THB)
- Silk scarves and clothing (100-800 THB)
- Wood carvings (150-2,000 THB)
- Handmade soaps and cosmetics (50-200 THB)
- Traditional Thai paintings (500-5,000 THB)

**Food Highlights**:
- Sai Oua (Northern Thai sausage): 40 THB
- Khao Soi (curry noodles): 50-70 THB
- Mango sticky rice: 60 THB
- Pad Thai: 40-60 THB
- Fresh fruit smoothies: 40 THB

**Israeli Tip**: The Sunday market is extremely crowded (50,000+ visitors weekly). Arrive at 4 PM when it opens to avoid the peak crowds at 6-8 PM. Many vendors speak basic English, and some even know Hebrew phrases from frequent Israeli customers!

**Getting There**:
- Grab/Bolt from anywhere in Chiang Mai: 50-100 THB
- Songthaew (red truck): 30 THB per person
- Walking from Nimman area: 20 minutes

---

### 2. Saturday Walking Street (ถนนคนเดินวันเสาร์)

**Location**: Wualai Road (South Gate area)
**Hours**: Every Saturday, 4 PM - 11 PM
**Best For**: Silver products, local crafts, less crowded than Sunday

**Why It''s Special**:
Located in the traditional silversmith district, this market offers excellent silver jewelry and metalwork. It''s slightly smaller than Sunday market but with better bargaining opportunities.

**What to Buy**:
- Sterling silver jewelry (300-3,000 THB)
- Leather goods (bags, wallets): 200-800 THB
- Handwoven textiles (500-2,000 THB)
- Ceramics and pottery (100-1,500 THB)
- Hill tribe crafts (100-600 THB)

**Food Section**:
Less crowded food area means faster service and fresher options. Try:
- Grilled fish (80-150 THB)
- Som Tam (papaya salad): 40 THB
- Coconut ice cream: 50 THB
- Roti (Thai pancake): 30-50 THB

**Israeli Insight**: Many Israeli travelers prefer Saturday market because it''s less overwhelming. The silver quality here is generally better than at Sunday market - look for "925" stamp on silver items.

**Bargaining Success**: Start at 50% of asking price. Vendors are more flexible here than at touristy Sunday market.

---

### 3. Night Bazaar (ไนท์บาซาร์)

**Location**: Chang Klan Road (near Night Bazaar area)
**Hours**: Every day, 6 PM - 12 AM
**Best For**: Convenience (open daily), souvenirs, tourist goods

**Why It''s Special**:
The only major night market open every day. Great if you miss the weekend markets or need last-minute shopping.

**What to Buy**:
- T-shirts and clothing (100-300 THB)
- Elephant pants (150-250 THB)
- Knock-off designer bags (300-800 THB)
- Phone cases and accessories (50-200 THB)
- Thai spices and tea (100-400 THB)

**Buildings to Explore**:
- **Kalare Night Bazaar**: Indoor section with AC
- **Anusarn Market**: Food court with live music
- **Ploen Ruedee Market**: Higher-end crafts

**Food Court**:
Large seating area with diverse options. Budget: 150-250 THB for full meal + drink.

**Warning**: Most touristy of all markets = highest prices. Expect to bargain hard. Quality varies significantly.

**Israeli Hangout**: Many Israeli travelers gather at the food court around 8-9 PM. You''ll often hear Hebrew being spoken!

---

## Hidden Gems: Local Markets

### 4. Ploen Ruedee Night Market (โปรดปรานเปลื้อง)

**Location**: Soi Ruamchok, near Chiang Mai Gate
**Hours**: Thursday-Sunday, 4 PM - 10 PM
**Best For**: Vintage items, unique finds, hipster vibe

**What Makes It Different**:
Curated selection of vintage clothing, retro items, and indie designers. More trendy and less traditional than other markets.

**Prices**: Generally 20-30% higher than walking streets, but unique items worth it.
**Vibe**: Young, hip crowd. Great music and atmosphere.

---

### 5. JJ Market (Jing Jai Market)

**Location**: Kamphaeng Din Road (near Superhighway)
**Hours**: Saturday-Sunday, 6 AM - 12 PM (morning market!)
**Best For**: Local experience, authentic prices, fresh produce

**Why Visit**:
99% locals, 1% tourists. Authentic northern Thai market experience with rock-bottom prices.

**What to Buy**:
- Fresh tropical fruits (10-50 THB per kilo)
- Thai street food breakfast (20-40 THB)
- Clothes at wholesale prices (50-150 THB)
- Local snacks and sweets (20-100 THB)

**Israeli Secret**: This is where Thai locals shop. Prices are 50-70% cheaper than tourist markets, but almost no English spoken. Use Google Translate or hand signals!

---

### 6. Chang Phueak Gate Night Market (ประตูช้างเผือก)

**Location**: Chang Phueak Gate (North Gate)
**Hours**: Daily, 5 PM - 11 PM
**Best For**: Food! (Not shopping)

**Food Focus**:
This is primarily a food market with limited shopping. Home of the famous "Cowboy Hat Lady" khao kha moo (braised pork leg over rice).

**Must-Try Dishes**:
- Khao Kha Moo (Cowboy Hat Lady): 40 THB
- Grilled pork skewers: 10 THB each
- Fried chicken: 80-120 THB per piece
- Thai-style pizza: 60 THB

**Budget**: 100-150 THB for very filling meal.

