## Shopping Smart: Bargaining Guide

### Starting Prices vs Final Price

| Item | Asking Price | Target Price | Final Price |
|------|--------------|--------------|-------------|
| Elephant pants | 250 THB | 150 THB | 150-180 THB |
| Silk scarf | 500 THB | 250 THB | 280-320 THB |
| Silver ring | 800 THB | 400 THB | 450-500 THB |
| T-shirt | 200 THB | 100 THB | 120-150 THB |
| Wood carving | 1,000 THB | 500 THB | 600-700 THB |

### Bargaining Rules

**Do''s**:
✅ Smile and be friendly (Thai people respond to warmth)
✅ Start at 40-50% of asking price
✅ Walk away if price too high (they often call you back)
✅ Buy multiple items from same vendor for better discount
✅ Carry small bills (vendors give better deals if you have exact change)
✅ Compare prices at 3-4 stalls before buying

**Don''ts**:
❌ Never bargain aggressively or rudely
❌ Don''t insult the product quality
❌ Don''t bargain for tiny amounts (20 THB difference is ~₪2)
❌ Don''t agree to a price then walk away
❌ Don''t touch items roughly (especially silver/crafts)

### Magic Phrases for Bargaining

**Thai**:
- "แพงไป" (phaeng bpai) - "Too expensive"
- "ลดได้ไหม" (lót dâai mǎi) - "Can you reduce?"
- "ราคาสุดท้าย" (raa-khaa sùt-tháai) - "Final price?"
- "ขอ...บาท" (khǒr...bàat) - "I want...[X] baht"

**Israeli Tip**: Many vendors know "Yoter zol?" (יותר זול?) - "Cheaper?" from Israeli customers!

